commit f296248a7b032d801c5e83f8de8faff65215038f
Author: Clifford Yapp <238416+starseeker@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Wed Jun 5 11:04:02 2024 -0400

    lint option added, and bot decimate -f does appear to be useful for such cases.

commit 71388eeb8dada4c55d7cdad58bb158df562174a9
Author: Clifford Yapp <238416+starseeker@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Wed Jun 5 10:06:43 2024 -0400

    Add an option to limit lint reporting based on triangle size
    
    We can't do it for all shotlines - if we miss a small triangle somewhere other
    than at the shotline origin, we won't know about it in the callbacks - but add
    an option to allow users to avoid reporting issues when the source triangles
    have a small area.
    
    In principle this shouldn't ever be necessary, but sufficiently small triangles
    are currently a problem for librt's BoT intersection routines and given we're
    deliberately sampling *every* triangle we're guaranteed to report all BoTs with
    such small triangles as invalid even if a ray hitting such a small face is
    highly improbable.
    
    Reporting the errors remains the default behavior, since the mesh in question
    really isn't behaving the way the raytracer expects even if it's a raytracing
    problem rather than a geometric problem per say, but this option gives users a
    way to determine what category of problem they are seeing and decide if the
    circumstances warrant using decimating to try and clear the small triangles.
    
    (Note: in testing, bot decimate -f 0.005 was able to produce a valid bot by
    clearing a small triangle, but the -e OpenMesh-based option isn't producing
    manifold output and doesn't repair successfully... arrgh.)

commit 1293de1b94e67d0b259135ed09d81e0663755056
Author: Clifford Yapp <238416+starseeker@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Wed Jun 5 07:24:29 2024 -0400

    Add a note on another filter option to add to lint

