Date:   Sat May 25 13:27:05 2024 -0400

    Fix bots.sh regression script
    
    Since bot flip is typically used only to repair an inside-out bot, we
    need to explicitly update the orientation in a case where we are
    intentionally creating a cw bot.
    
    Previously the rt_bot_flip function was also swapping the orientation.

commit ae4e26626f0adda3bfd1f9f9945b77afdf26a1c9
Author: Clifford Yapp <238416+starseeker@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Fri May 24 21:17:29 2024 -0400

    Rename function - more to this than just thinness

commit d41931f0113669471728c2a524a21f22bb54f328
Author: Clifford Yapp <238416+starseeker@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Fri May 24 21:07:37 2024 -0400

    Should probably explore what sort of correctness check we can do on the facetization results with shotlining.  rtcheck on two copies of a bad mesh visually showed 'missing' areas where there should have been overlaps and weren't - we might be able to use original facetization inputs as a 'ground truth' check to make sure our solid shotlines from the bots seem sane.

commit 24fd2930812aea2a80988ac5fcfb6c98ae75c8a3
Author: Clifford Yapp <238416+starseeker@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Fri May 24 21:01:03 2024 -0400

    Note we may have different categories of problem to spot and either handle or simply report.

commit ebf7d2abc5303743fc04b1131c2d11832962ce3f
Author: Clifford Yapp <238416+starseeker@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Fri May 24 20:53:58 2024 -0400

    Experiment with looking 'above' the triangles.
    
    Studying the r.rot348 havoc example, I'm becoming convinced CSG
    intervention is the only practical way to resolve interior triangle
    issues like that.  We'll go ahead and attempt repairs, since some
    categories of problem can be fixed that way, but resolving the rot348
    case would require (at a minimum) removing all the coplanar triangles
    involved in the interference, which center ray testing won't catch, and
    even then it might be too much for the hole filling algorithm.

commit 6886076f47d043e15c6fb260a7f1cbca374969b5
Author: Clifford Yapp <238416+starseeker@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Fri May 24 19:31:58 2024 -0400

    Add some notes about further testing needed.
    
    The repair step isn't clearing all issues despite reporting valid
    meshes, and examination reveals that's because of interior coplanar
    faces impacting solid shotline results.  We'll need to find a way to
    identify not just the thin triangles filling holes, but also the
    interior triangles messing with shotline results.  The latter are less
    startling visually but arguably much more important analytically, since
    they will negatively impact things like rtweight.
    
    It looks as if hit_surfno is recording the triangles associated with
    hits, so we should have enough info to identify our problem areas if we
    shoot the right rays.  More work ahead.

commit f59a51aa6d52ea80e6437c56090f27b350dec65e
Author: Clifford Yapp <238416+starseeker@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Fri May 24 16:19:10 2024 -0400

    Expose the "remove degenerate thickness faces" feature as a "bot strip" subcommand
    
    Even if the default settings aren't able to repair these meshes, it may be that
    manual intervention with more aggressive bot repair settings can.  Failing
    that, this allows the modeler to remove the problematic faces and prepare a BoT
    for export to other tools for additional repair work.  For that reason, no
    attempt is made to automatically repair the output as part of the strip process
    - if there are any problematic triangles, the resulting bot will be
    non-manifold until repaired.
    
    Going ahead and defining this command rather than capturing the intermediate
    results from facetize to avoid complexity in the facetize code, as well as
    provide more flexibility for users.
    
    The lint command can produce a list of bot objects that will make sense to
    consider as possible inputs for this command.  Note that providing non-manifold
    inputs to this command will likely remove triangles in unexpected ways since
    there is a risk that the rays shotting from the triangles centers will have
    nothing on the opposite side of the mesh to hit.

commit 9cf5336f2158330210eaaafa9b69fef7b6e5f6be
Author: Clifford Yapp <238416+starseeker@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Fri May 24 15:58:04 2024 -0400

    Able to do some thin faces removal and repairs, but (pretty much as expected) Geogram can't handle all cases.

