commit 984c7d8cdbd392abbe2fdb806279409f69e8e875
Author: Clifford Yapp <238416+starseeker@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Thu May 23 19:05:59 2024 -0400

    Add a lint check for bots with thin face thicknesses
    
    Although the Manifold boolean usually succeeds, it sometimes does so
    when faced with coplanar faces by producing extremely close together
    faces that raytrace with zero thickness but still show up as hits in
    nirt and when drawing the geometry.
    
    We test for this case by finding the center point of each triangle,
    backing it off slightly from the triangle plane, and shooting in the
    opposite direction of the triangle normal into the mesh.  We then check
    the first partition distance to see if that face is part of one of these
    degenerate volume pairings.  If such a case is found, abort the test and
    report a problem case.
    
    The "fix" for this is typically going to be to tweak the parent CSG
    solid definitions to avoid the coplanar faces.  It's probable the zero
    distance partitions can also be filtered and ignored analytically in the
    solid shotlining cases (rtweight, for example, won't add weight from a
    zero length segment), but they remain a visual distraction.
    Topologically these *are* valid meshes, but if we can it would be good
    to find a way to eliminate the coplanarity artifacts.
    
    One possibility that suggests itself, given the new repair capabilities,
    would be to analyze all faces on the mesh and flag any with this
    characteristic for removal.  We could then apply the bot repair logic to
    the mesh with the zero distance faces removed to create a new valid
    manifold.  Need to experiment and see if that would work - not entirely
    sure if the repair logic could handle the sort of inputs that process
    would produce.

commit 7e7b714415da79e5ba900c56d84ab2a20816fb10
Author: Clifford Yapp <238416+starseeker@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Thu May 23 14:17:03 2024 -0400

    Add a way to determine if a BoT is inside-out
    
    Usually we end up spotting these cases when a shaded solid drawing winds
    up black instead of red, even with no color set on the object.  Add a
    way to programmatically detect when this is happening, so we can try to
    either do something about it automatically or at least report the
    situation to the modeler without them having to manually draw and
    inspect the solids to spot it.

commit 8d8f83d6beddf5ef993a039d47d27536b0ad0a4e
Author: Clifford Yapp <238416+starseeker@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Thu May 23 13:50:33 2024 -0400

    Fix shaded drawing of BoTs in CW mode
    
    Noticed this working with bot flip - the bot flip code (incorrectly, as
    it happens, given the intent there) was changing the orientation of the
    bot from RT_BOT_CCW to RT_BOT_CW, but the shaded display was still
    showing the bot as inside-out even though the orientation on the
    "flipped" geometry was in fact changed.  Dug a bit, and the poly drawing
    routine was ignoring the orientation flag when supplying drawing
    instructions.

