commit ab502bb3a4d6bde6d714525175c93fc3db123027
Author: Clifford Yapp <238416+starseeker@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Wed May 22 11:23:43 2024 -0400

    By default, limit mesh repair to holes less than or equal to five percent of the mesh area.  Add controls for bot repair so the user can adjust.  Should probably allow adjusting that for facetize eventually, bot for now just using the default.

commit 1f8cd64eb70ebc386cb381e2ac1be48d575db17d
Author: Clifford Yapp <238416+starseeker@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Tue May 21 20:41:17 2024 -0400

    Update src/bext submodule to get librt+geogram gchecker fix
    
    It turns out the gchecker failure in Windows Release mode was due to
    linking in a geogram built without the win32 building patches.
    
    The symptoms were that gchecker would launch but hang, with bu_parallel
    launching its threads but failing to start its workers successfully.
    Even commenting out the actual guts of the work function still resulted
    in hanging, indicating the problem was with the parallelism itself.
    Bisecting identified the commit merging bext usage into the facetize
    branch as the point where the regression first appeared, and commenting
    out the librt usage of geogram in that commit resulted in success.
    
    dumpbin /dependents geogram.dll on the failing geogram build produced a
    very short dependencies list, which may be related.  In any case, it
    looks like the latest bext patch does succeed in allowing gchecker to
    run again.

