commit 7b113a5f23a8e76d7461502685003b90a5f25808
Author: Clifford Yapp <238416+starseeker@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Fri May 17 16:32:11 2024 -0400

    See if we can add /DEBUG to Release MSVC build
    
    Grr.  Getting a regress-gchecker failure unique to Release mode -
    libanalyze perform_raytracing function calls bu_parallel, and in Release
    mode on Windows everything hangs.  Doesn't appear to be related to the
    contents of analyze_worker - commenting out its internals and making it
    a no-op doesn't alleviate the hanging, but launching bu_parallel with
    ncpus==1 succeeds.  Haven't been able to get a backtrace so far.  Trying
    this, even though early results don't seem to be too promising...
    
    Failure is especially bizarre since parallel rt is still succeeding.
    There must be a setup difference somewhere.

commit d9c0adaf73c8545fb213d5a8c573f8a87f04ae10
Author: Clifford Yapp <238416+starseeker@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Fri May 17 15:15:09 2024 -0400

    Initialize point values to zero (fixes drawing of label line in Windows Debug mode)

commit 5a479621557fe4c80fd065cf4253f2fdd825c7fc
Author: Clifford Yapp <238416+starseeker@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Fri May 17 10:39:08 2024 -0400

    Adjust how brep_loop_points is allocated
    
    We were getting the following warning in Release mode with gcc on Linux:
    
    src/libbrep/cdt/fast.cpp:2067:97: error: argument 1 value
    ‘18446744073709551615’ exceeds maximum object size 9223372036854775807
    [-Werror=alloc-size-larger-than=]
     2067 |     ON_SimpleArray<BrepTrimPoint> *brep_loop_points = new ON_SimpleArray<BrepTrimPoint>[loop_cnt];
          |
    ^ /usr/include/c++/13/new:128:26: note: in a call to allocation function
    ‘operator new []’ declared here
      128 | _GLIBCXX_NODISCARD void* operator new[](std::size_t) _GLIBCXX_THROW (std::bad_alloc)
    
    To avoid this we instead make a pointer array and create the
    BrepTrimPoint arrays individually.  In practice loop_cnt probably
    wouldn't have gotten big enough to produce an array object that would
    hit this limit, but in principle it IS possible (i.e. the data types
    don't preclude it.)

commit faf47ffa4545ddb23f596bc4480468bccea2e4d8
Author: Clifford Yapp <238416+starseeker@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Thu May 16 19:10:24 2024 -0400

    Try removing the if(WIN32) block from FindGeogram.cmake

