commit 86546a9accc61263b2c9c63e7c491c29368a51fe
Author: Clifford Yapp <238416+starseeker@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Tue May 7 16:06:16 2024 -0400

    Update v020 ctrl image for basic drawing test

commit 1901243e7404d4e3310b7ee1fe184e470c22f67b
Author: Clifford Yapp <238416+starseeker@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Tue May 7 15:20:49 2024 -0400

    Only use subprocess.h where we need to

commit 6dbeeb9fa467acb6f86fce27e919b0eac901cb36
Author: Clifford Yapp <238416+starseeker@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Tue May 7 15:10:12 2024 -0400

    Use Chris's updates to subprocess.h to launch ged_tessellate
    
    OK, so this is a little complicated... the current iteration of the
    libbu process API doesn't include support for async reads.  The changes
    for doing so are rather invasive, and given the other cleanup work it
    would be a lot to try to add them until the dust has settled.
    
    Chris also did some work to pull in the upstream proposed patch for Unix
    async I/O support and also worked to get subprocess.h to handle async on
    Windows - while not yet passing all the upstream tests, he did meet with
    some success.  We will try that version of subprocess.h for launching
    the ged_tessellate executable, and experiment with the async I/O
    capabilities it provides.  This is a self-contained change for just
    facetize - the other libbu changes are unaffected.
    
    Async I/O is of particular interest in this situation because we want to
    eventually provide more useful intermediate status info from
    ged_tessellate to its parent as it is working.  We need an async read
    capabilities for that, since there is no guarantee ged_tessellate will
    produce output at all and we can't have the parent libged hanging
    indefinitely waiting for input that might not come.

commit a791f70eacedbde9847e2de98baa2f7a0f0b317c
Author: Clifford Yapp <238416+starseeker@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Tue May 7 13:51:52 2024 -0400

    For the moment, don't do the post-timeout reads

commit 667ab1a6655f7a0e968d318694886704265aeb99
Author: Clifford Yapp <238416+starseeker@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Tue May 7 12:37:28 2024 -0400

    Be more selective about what primitives we're looking at as leaves, and filter inputs to db_walk_tree

commit 2d2a6e6ab3626e4e97fe67afa40e6907dbbe5836
Author: f4alt <christopherjmacgregor@gmail.com>
Date:   Tue May 7 01:05:21 2024 -0400

    cleanup commented out code
    
    after further testing, it looks like we can get away with checking the
    WNOHANG wait() as long as we protect the bu_process_wait from re-waiting
    on the same pid.
    
    only caveat is the alive check could now end up 'eating' the error code
    from being returned by process_wait().. not sure there's a clean way to
    avoid that

commit 8d6c9db900bf2d66f3e7af73a90cd5499ece2cb1
Author: Clifford Yapp <238416+starseeker@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Mon May 6 20:32:21 2024 -0400

    Restore ability to specify top level comb name to hold -r mode outputs.

commit 061758818228cab502b4988b1043b286cc7cd683
Author: f4alt <christopherjmacgregor@gmail.com>
Date:   Mon May 6 16:16:49 2024 -0400

    sanity null-termination

commit c11db6d235887e340ba121c2a28fdc7a664e69e6
Author: f4alt <christopherjmacgregor@gmail.com>
Date:   Mon May 6 16:10:19 2024 -0400

    wip - update 'alive' checking on linux
    
    kill(pid, 0) is not quite enough for our use cases. If a process
    finishes, it will still report alive until it is waited on - which is
    not what we want. Instead, attempt to wait on the process and report
    that status as its alive state.
    
    Still need to test to make sure we can't double wait (ie infinite hang) on a
    process that's been waited for in 'alive' before calling bu_process_wait

commit 2b9ab24c90cfc94225a797d77e2a4a2b6ef9cfa9
Author: Clifford Yapp <238416+starseeker@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Mon May 6 13:57:13 2024 -0400

    Empty comb trees will have no objects, but can still 'succeed' by producing an empty bot.

