commit 5c8602c63235bd7a95f3932305f3e88f297302a4
Author: Clifford Yapp <238416+starseeker@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Wed Apr 17 13:32:42 2024 -0400

    Add bot check man page, note new man pages in NEWS file.

commit 81fad6afcda2c8531b9ef06ec7995b835bcd0d30
Author: Clifford Yapp <238416+starseeker@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Wed Apr 17 13:29:58 2024 -0400

    Add test files for libged bot commands

commit 0b879bb5868831065092dac96509b0bb99bc558c
Author: Clifford Yapp <238416+starseeker@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Wed Apr 17 13:24:42 2024 -0400

    bot extrude enhancement to produce an evaluated BoT
    
    Taking advantage of the Manifold boolean abilities, we are able to
    properly realize the "bot extrude" feature and produce a mesh that is
    the result of the evaluated CSG tree of primitives generated to
    represent the implicit volume of a plate mode BoT explicitly.  The comb
    tree that was previously produced can still be generated with the -C
    option, but this is not recommended as those comb trees can be very
    large and difficult to work with.
    
    For large plate mode BoTs the extrusion process may be rather slow - the
    boolean problem involved with evaluating the union of all individual
    elements of the extrusion is difficult - but the output should be a
    properly manifold representation of the plate mode volume.
    
    Note that the output volume is ultimately an approximation of the
    implicit plate mode volume - even in the simplest cases there can be
    view dependent behavior of plate mode BoTs depending on incoming ray
    angles.  Plate modes where the hit distance is always extruded out in
    the direction of the ray are ignored - such behaviors are not
    representable with volumetric geometry, and the standard "extrude in
    both directions from the middle" volume will be generated regardless.

commit fed15b002d241b04c64f41e3a082d40986e38ae8
Author: Clifford Yapp <238416+starseeker@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Wed Apr 17 13:14:17 2024 -0400

    Expose the Manifold check as a bot check cmd
    
    Manifold library's validity testing is key for determining whether a
    given BoT is viable for boolean evaluation, so wire it in to the bot
    check command.  It's added to the default checks and "solid" (solid is
    the test implicitly selected when no specific test is asked for.)  The
    specific Manifold test can also be run in isolation with the "manifold"
    subcommand:
    
       bot check manifold input.bot
    
    A warning will be printed if BRL-CAD's routines and Manifold disagree -
    such a case probably warrants investigation to see if there is a
    problem in either testing setup.

commit 48291aa52bc6c1be85ed55d8779891b986cf61e7
Author: Clifford Yapp <238416+starseeker@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Wed Apr 17 13:10:35 2024 -0400

    check subcommand is using Manifold directly, so find and list it

commit 7d0102f51a578f557a2d57c852c0d427d9d2adee
Author: Clifford Yapp <238416+starseeker@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Wed Apr 17 13:05:31 2024 -0400

    Shouldn't be using these libs directly in bot, with the repair logic moved to librt

commit 14b1b29ab80cfd731cbb2dd368cdea236da2bad1
Author: Clifford Yapp <238416+starseeker@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Wed Apr 17 12:52:12 2024 -0400

    Add bot repair command to expose Geogram hole filling
    
    The "repair" subcommand to the libged "bot" command will check if a mesh
    is manifold.  If not, it tries to use the Geogram library's hole filling
    routines to produce a manifold mesh.  It can either write out the new
    mesh in-place, or to a user-supplied object name.
    
    Note that this is intended to repair relatively small holes in nearly
    manifold meshes - if a mesh is sufficiently messy, the original modeling
    intent is lost and even a "repaired" mesh may not be very representative
    of what an actual human modeler would have reconstructed.

commit c76083c401a786a862d8a5fe251a2f7b20b037f8
Author: Clifford Yapp <238416+starseeker@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Wed Apr 17 12:28:41 2024 -0400

    Add function to apply Geogram hole filling to bots
    
    This is the core logic used to apply Geogram's hole filling algorithm to
    rt_bot_internal data.  At some point we'll probably want to allow
    passing in a threshold parameter to control how aggressive the hole
    filling should be - right now it basically tries to fill ANY hole.

