    Merge main into facetize

commit 457c1ad4fa29c4e911acea70ec5e35e5547efec6
Author: Clifford Yapp <238416+starseeker@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Tue Apr 2 19:02:51 2024 -0400

    Note where to go to find the definition logic for the *_deps variables.

commit 2a6eede5d50563c9954d6181cd438fd4ba675b68
Author: Clifford Yapp <238416+starseeker@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Tue Apr 2 16:34:03 2024 -0400

    List file for CMake

commit 4cd547ee4c788db8d6caf9e9090aeb80bdc62003
Author: Clifford Yapp <238416+starseeker@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Tue Apr 2 16:17:38 2024 -0400

    Consoliate find_package resets into BRLCAD_Find_Package
    
    Per suggestion from Sean, most (but not all) of the find_package cases respect
    a similar pattern.  Rather than have one macro per package, it would be better
    to make a generic wrapper that handles most of the cases and use it.
    
    The key to making this work is the CACHE_VARIABLES directory property, which
    gives us a way to get a "before and after" insight into what a find_package
    call has done to the cache.  Once we know that, we can use unset(CACHE) to
    clear those values from the cache.  We also make sure to save and then restore
    the values to the working variable state, so we don't destroy the find_package
    results for the working session.
    
    We do, however, still need something in the cache so the BRL-CAD Summary
    printing knows what happened - the find_package variables are scoped in their
    calling directories and aren't directly visible.  To handle this, we write out
    a *_STATUS variable for each package and teach the Summary logic to look for
    it.  The *_STATUS variable isn't functional, so it is harmless as far as
    find_package is concerned, but it still gives us what we need for the final
    summary.  Nor does it matter that the value will be overwritten by mulitple
    calls, since the results of multiple BRLCAD_Find_Package calls with the same
    package should always be the same.  (If not, it is an error.)

commit 44a51f8666d7f4cf0e2073e5a1657425607d0df5
Author: Clifford Yapp <238416+starseeker@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Mon Apr 1 19:15:15 2024 -0400

    Try a different approach to tclIndex/pkgIndex
    
    We're still getting occasional problems with errors generating these
    files in parallel builds.  Take the build targets out of the equation
    and generate a script that executes each command in order.  Then run
    that script with a single custom target and custom command.
    
    Needs testing in multiconfig environments - not sure if $<CONFIG> will
    do what needs doing here...

